      "role": "user",
      "content": "hey i'm studying for my physics final and im kinda stuck on quantum entanglement. can u give me a quick summary of what it actually is and how it's different from just regular classical correlation? i dont need the heavy math right now just a conceptual explanation",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Quantum entanglement is like a pair of magical twin wands that, when you wave one, the other wields a wave of its own, no matter how far apart they are. Imagine you have two wands, and when you wave one, the other wand waves back instantly, even if it's on the other side of the world. This is different from classical correlation, where things are more like two separate wands that can only wave back if you wave them at the same time, and only if they're close enough to see each other. In the quantum realm, these twin wands are entangled, and their connection is so strong that they seem to communicate faster than the speed of light, defying our usual understanding of space and time. It's like having a secret language between the wands that no one else can understand.",
